<taxonomicName family="Selaginellaceae" genus="S." infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. monospora var. ciliolata" order="Selaginellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="variety" species="monospora" variety="ciliolata">S. monospora var. ciliolata</taxonomicName>
W.M. Chu (in 
<bibRefCitation author="Chu, WM" journalOrPublisher="20, 35 - 93" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B3" refString="Chu, WM, 2006. Selaginellaceae. In: Wu CY (Ed.) Flora Yunnanica. Science Press, Beijing, Vol. 20, 35-93" title="Selaginellaceae. In: Wu CY (Ed.) Flora Yunnanica. Science Press, Beijing, Vol." year="2006">Chu 2006</bibRefCitation>
) and listed in the &quot;Uncertain taxa&quot; in Flora of China (
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang, XC" editor="Wu, ZY" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing and Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St. Louis, Vols 2 - 3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="37 - 66" refId="B35" refString="Zhang, XC, Nooteboom, HP, Kato, M, 2013. Selaginellaceae. In: Wu, ZY, Raven, PH, Hong, DY, Eds., Flora of China. Science Press, Beijing and Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St. Louis, Vols 2-3: 37 - 66" title="Selaginellaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of China." year="2013">Zhang et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
: 66) has many similarities in morphological features with 
<taxonomicName family="Selaginellaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. trichophylla" order="Selaginellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trichophylla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. trichophylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The only distinct feature is the spinules on the upper side of the leaves, but these are not always present and it is likely that this trait is associated with a more humid habitat.
</paragraph>
